DataElement.preferredName: Study Subject Clinical Trial Experience Document Version Uniform Resource Locator ISO21090.TEL.URL.v1.0
DataElement.preferredDefinition: A document capturing the actual end-to-end (or beginning to point-in-time) experience of a single study subject within the context of a particular study. A complete or local reference to a website, ftp, file path or other location from which the document contents can be retrieved. NOTE(S): Local references should only be used when communicating between systems capable of resolving the local reference.

DataElementConcept.preferredName: Study Subject Clinical Trial Experience Document Version Uniform Resource Locator
DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: A matter or an individual that is observed, analyzed, examined, investigated, experimented upon, or/and treated in the course of a particular study.:A research study that prospectively assigns human participants or groups of humans to one or more health-related interventions to evaluate the effects on health outcomes. Interventions include but are not restricted to drugs, cells and other biological products, surgical procedures, radiologic procedures, devices, behavioral treatments, process-of-care changes, and preventive care.:The accumulation of knowledge or skill that results from direct participation in events or activities.:A physical object, or electronic counterpart, that is characterized by containing writing which is meant to be human-readable.:A form or variant of a type or original; one of a sequence of copies of a program, each incorporating new modifications._A Uniform Resource Locator is an Internet address which tells a browser where to find an Internet resource. (from http://www.computeruser.com)

Concepts.definition: A matter or an individual that is observed, analyzed, examined, investigated, experimented upon, or/and treated in the course of a particular study.
A research study that prospectively assigns human participants or groups of humans to one or more health-related interventions to evaluate the effects on health outcomes.
The accumulation of knowledge or skill that results from direct participation in events or activities.
A physical object, or electronic counterpart, that is characterized by containing writing which is meant to be human-readable.
A form or variant of a type or original; one of a sequence of copies of a program, each incorporating new modifications.
